19613, -0.017306363210082054, -0.03364992514252663, -0.005060727242380381, -0.036682747304439545, -0.04079872742295265, 0.00945350993424654, -0.009008214809000492, 0.028186023235321045, 0.009369265288114548, -0.007991255261003971, -0.023444224148988724, 0.024286676198244095, 0.02551424875855446, -0.013515330851078033, 0.01529651414602995, 0.046021927148103714, -0.018738530576229095, 0.03600878641009331, -0.012672878801822662, 0.03458865359425545, -0.008905916474759579, -0.013635681010782719, 0.03605692833662033, 0.03131512925028801, -0.01936435140669346, 0.011595744639635086, 0.0010184637503698468, -0.02503284625709057, 0.01843765564262867, -0.001300534582696855, 0.030544888228178024, -0.010115436278283596, -0.0065831574611365795, -0.0198457520455122, 0.004046776331961155, -0.015103953890502453, -0.012299792841076851, 0.0005460891406983137, -0.02731950208544731, 0.03884905204176903]], "input": ["\"PERFORMANCE ANALYSIS\":\"Performance analysis involves analyzing and evaluating past performance using the results of variance analysis.\"", "\"THE CONCEPT OF VARIANCES\":\"The concept of variances includes basic variances for materials price and usage, assuming a single type of material, while real-world products often use multiple materials.\"", "\"SALES MIX VARIANCE\":Sales mix variance compares the actual quantities of goods sold to the actual quantities sold at the standard mix. It measures the effect of selling a different mix of products than the budgeted mix, evaluated using the standard contribution per unit. This variance shows the impact on contribution or profit of selling a different mix compared to the standard. An adverse mix variance indicates that customers are buying less of the higher-margin products and are instead purchasing lower-margin products. By analyzing sales mix variance, businesses can understand how changes in the sales mix impact overall profitability.", "\"SALES QUANTITY VARIANCE\":\"Sales quantity variance\" compares the actual quantity of goods sold in the standard mix with the budgeted quantity sold in the standard mix. It measures the effect on contribution or profit of selling a different quantity than budgeted. This variance evaluates the impact of the actual total sales volume differing from the budgeted total sales volume, using the standard contribution per unit. By assessing the variation in the total quantity of products sold compared to the budgeted quantity, sales quantity variance helps in understanding how changes in total sales volume affect overall profitability. An adverse variance may be due to factors such as poor economic conditions or the emergence of a new competitor, and it identifies elements that influence the sales of all products.", "\"MIX VARIANCE\":\"MIX VARIANCE\" is a metric used to measure the effect of using different proportions of materials compared to the standard mix. It is calculated using the formula: Mix variance = (Actual mix percentage - Budgeted mix percentage) x Total actual quantity x Standard contribution per unit. This metric helps in understanding how changes in the mix of materials impact overall costs.", "\"YIELD VARIANCE\":\"Yield variance\" is calculated as the difference between the actual output and the expected output, given the input, multiplied by the standard cost per unit. It measures the difference between the actual output and the expected output based on the actual input, and it helps in understanding the efficiency of the production process. Additionally, yield variance indicates whether the production process was more or less efficient than expected, based on the standard input quantities.", "\"EXAMPLE OF MIX AND YIELD VARIANCES\":\"A perfume is made by mixing essential oils with alcohol. Essential oils cost $15,000 per litre. Alcohol costs $10 per litre. In the standard, 1% of the liquid input is essential oil, and 99% is alcohol. If the production manager uses more oil and less alcohol, this would lead to a more expensive mix, as essential oil costs more than alcohol. This would result in an adverse mix variance. A normal loss of 37.5% of input occurs when making one litre of perfume. Therefore, the standard specifies using 1.6 litres of liquid to make one litre. If the production manager inputs 1.6 litres of inputs and produces more than 1 litre, this would result in a favourable yield variance.\"", "\"CALCULATING THE MIX VARIANCE\":\"A tabular approach best illustrates how to calculate the mix variance: Actual quantity used (column A) describes the actual amount of each material employed in production. Actual quantity in the standard mix equals the total actual quantity used (total column A) multiplied by the standard proportions. The quantity totals for columns A and B will be the same. Variance due to materials mix equals the third column multiplied by the standard price for each unit of input.\"", "\"CALCULATING YIELD VARIANCE\":\"The yield variance compares actual output with the output expected based on the actual input. It amounts to the difference between expected and actual output multiplied by standard cost per unit.\"", "\"QUIZ: MATERIALS MIX AND YIELD\":\"This quiz involves calculating various material variances, including total materials cost, materials price, materials mix, materials yield, and materials usage, based on given data for a product's standard and actual material usage and costs.\"", "\"SALES VOLUME VARIANCES\":", "\"MATERIALS MIX VARIANCE\":\"Materials mix variance\" measures the difference between the actual mix of materials used in production and the standard mix, valued at the standard cost. It indicates whether more or less of certain materials were used than expected. For Material X, the actual quantity used is 9,900 kg compared to the standard mix of 10,133 kg, resulting in a favorable variance of $699. For Material Y, the actual quantity used is 5,300 kg compared to the standard mix of 5,067 kg, resulting in an adverse variance of $466. The total materials mix variance is $233 favorable.", "\"MATERIALS YIELD VARIANCE\":\"Materials yield variance is calculated by comparing the actual output with the expected yield based on the standard usage. The actual output is 5,000 units, while the expected yield is 5,067 units, resulting in an adverse variance of $536. An alternative approach calculates the variance by comparing the actual quantity in the standard mix with the standard quantity for actual output, resulting in an adverse variance of $533.\"", "\"MATERIALS MIX AND YIELD QUIZ\":\"The quiz for Materials Mix and Yield involves calculating the materials mix variance and yield variance for Chemical X, which is made by combining three substances in a furnace. The standard cost and actual inputs are provided, and the variances are calculated based on the differences between actual and standard quantities and costs.\"", "\"TOTAL MATERIALS COST VARIANCE\":", "\"STANDARD PROPORTIONS\":\"Standard proportions are the predetermined ratios of materials expected to be used in production. For example, Material A: 60%, Material B: 20%, Material C: 20%.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}